SIMPLE: hook
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hook
<hw>Hook</hw> <pr>(h⟦oocr⟧k; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hok</ets>, AS. <ets>h⟦omac⟧c</ets>; cf. D. <ets>haak</ets>, G.
<ets>hake</ets>, <ets>haken</ets>, OHG. <ets>h⟦amac⟧ko</ets>,
<ets>h⟦amac⟧go</ets>, <ets>h⟦amac⟧ggo</ets>, Icel. <ets>haki</ets>, Sw.
<ets>hake</ets>, Dan. <ets>hage</ets>. Cf. <er>Arquebuse</er>,
<er>Hagbut</er>, <er>Hake</er>, <er>Hatch</er> a half door,
<er>Heckle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A piece of metal, or other hard
material, formed or bent into a curve or at an angle, for catching,
holding, or sustaining anything; <as>as, a <ex>hook</ex> for catching
fish; a <ex>hook</ex> for fastening a gate; a boat <ex>hook</ex>,
etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That part of a hinge which is fixed to a post, and
on which a door or gate hangs and turns.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An implement for cutting grass or grain; a sickle;
an instrument for cutting or lopping; a billhook.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like slashing Bentley with his desperate <qex>hook</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Steam Engin.)</fld> <def>See <er>Eccentric</er>,
and <er>V-hook</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A snare; a trap.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A field sown two years in succession.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The projecting points of the thigh
bones of cattle; -- called also <altname>hook bones</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Geog.)</fld> <def>A spit or narrow cape of sand or
gravel turned landward at the outer end; <as>as, Sandy <ex>Hook</ex> in
New Jersey</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Sports)</fld> <def>The curving motion of a ball, as
in bowling or baseball, curving away from the hand which threw the ball;
in golf, a curving motion in the direction of the golfer who struck the
ball.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <def>A procedure within the
encoding of a computer program which allows the user to modify the
program so as to import data from or export data to other
programs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>By hook or by crook</b></col>, <cd>one way or other; by
any means, direct or indirect.</cd> <au>Milton.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧In hope her
to attain <xex>by hook or crook</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Spenser.</au> --
<col><b>Off the hook</b></col>, <cd>freed from some obligation or
difficulty; <as>as, to get <ex>off the hook</ex> by getting someone else
to do the job</as>.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>Off the
hooks</b></col>, <cd>unhinged; disturbed; disordered.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧In the evening, by water, to the Duke of
Albemarle, whom I found mightly <xex>off the hooks</xex> that the ships
are not gone out of the river.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Pepys.</au><-- = out of joint
--> -- <col><b>On one's own hook</b></col>, <cd>on one's own account or
responsibility; by one's self.</cd> <mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark>
<au>Bartlett.</au> -- <col><b>To go off the hooks</b></col>, <cd>to
die.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <au>Thackeray.</au> -- <col><b>Bid
hook</b></col>, <cd>a small boat hook.</cd> -- <col><b>Chain
hook</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Chain</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Deck
hook</b></col>, <cd>a horizontal knee or frame, in the bow of a ship, on
which the forward part of the deck rests.</cd> -- <col><b>Hook and
eye</b></col>, <cd>one of the small wire hooks and loops for fastening
together the opposite edges of a garment, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Hook
bill</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the strongly curved beak of a
bird.</cd> -- <col><b>Hook ladder</b></col>, <cd>a ladder with hooks at
the end by which it can be suspended, as from the top of a wall.</cd> --
<col><b>Hook motion</b></col> <fld>(Steam Engin.)</fld>, <cd>a valve
gear which is reversed by V hooks.</cd> -- <col><b>Hook squid</b></col>,
<cd>any squid which has the arms furnished with hooks, instead of
suckers, as in the genera <gen>Enoploteuthis</gen> and
<gen>Onychteuthis</gen>.</cd> -- <col><b>Hook wrench</b></col>, <cd>a
wrench or spanner, having a hook at the end, instead of a jaw, for
turning a bolthead, nut, or coupling.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hook</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hook
<hw>Hook</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hooked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hooking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To catch or fasten
with a hook or hooks; to seize, capture, or hold, as with a hook, esp.
with a disguised or baited hook; hence, to secure by allurement or
artifice; to entrap; to catch; <as>as, to <ex>hook</ex> a dress; to
<ex>hook</ex> a trout.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Hook</qex> him, my poor dear, . . . at any sacrifice.</q>
<rj><qau>W. Collins.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To seize or pierce with the points of the horns, as
cattle in attacking enemies; to gore.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To steal.</def> <mark>[Colloq. Eng. &
U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To hook on</b></col>, <cd>to fasten or attach by, or as
by, hook.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hook</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hook
<hw>Hook</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bend;
to curve as a hook.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move or go with a sudden turn;</def>
<specif>hence</specif> <mark>[Slang or Prov. Eng.]</mark>, <def>to make
off; to clear out; -- often with <xex>it</xex>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Duncan was
wounded, and the escort <xex>hooked</xex> it.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Kipling.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hookah</ent>⟦br⟧
